<DOC><DOCNO> AP890821-0154 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0844EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv01   08-21 0501</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv01,0523</SECOND><HEAD>$adv01</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Friday, Sept. 1</HEAD><HEAD>Today In History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Friday, September 1, the 244th day of 1989. There are121 days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   Fifty years ago, on September 1, 1939, World War II began as NaziGermany invaded Poland. Great Britain and France declared waragainst Germany two days later.   On this date:   In 1807, former Vice President Aaron Burr was found innocent oftreason.   In 1878, Emma M. Nutt became the first woman telephone operatorin the United States, for the Telephone Despatch Company of Boston.   In 1905, Alberta and Saskatchewan entered Confederation as theeighth and ninth provinces of Canada.   In 1923, the Japanese cities of Tokyo and Yokohama weredevastated by an earthquake that claimed some 150,000 lives.   In 1932, New York City Mayor James J. ``Gentleman Jimmy'' Walkerresigned following charges of graft and corruption in hisadministration.   In 1945, Americans received word of Japan's formal surrender,ending World War II. (Because of the time difference, it wasSeptember 2 in Tokyo Bay, where the surrender took place.)   In 1951, the United States, Australia and New Zealand signed amutual defense pact that came to be known as the ANZUS treaty.   In 1961, the Soviet Union ended a moratorium on atomic testingwith an above-ground nuclear explosion in central Asia.   In 1969, a coup in Libya brought Moammar Gadhafi to power.   In 1972, American Bobby Fischer won the international chess crownin Reykjavik, Iceland, by defeating Soviet player Boris Spassky intheir final match.   In 1976, U.S. Rep. Wayne L. Hays, D-Ohio, resigned in the wake ofa scandal in which he admitted having an affair with secretaryElizabeth Ray.   In 1983, 269 people were killed when a Korean Air Lines Boeing747 was shot down by a Soviet jet fighter after the airliner enteredSoviet airspace.   In 1983, Henry ``Scoop'' Jackson, a 30-year Senate veteran knownfor his liberal views on social issues and a hawkish stand onnational defense, died in Everett, Wash., at age 71.   Ten years ago: Hurricane David tore across the DominicanRepublic, leaving hundreds of dead in its wake, before slashingacross the Windward Passage into the mountains of eastern Cuba. ThePioneer 11 space probe survived two crossings through debriscircling the ringed planet Saturn.   Five years ago: The astronauts aboard the shuttle Discoverylaunched their third commercial satellite in three days.   One year ago: Shipyard workers at Gdansk, Poland, ended aneleven-day strike, acting with some reluctance on the advice ofSolidarity leader Lech Walesa.   Today's Birthdays: Former Defense Secretary Melvin Laird is 67.Actress Yvonne De Carlo is 65. Country singer Conway Twitty is 56.Conductor Seiji Ozawa is 54. Comedian-actress Lily Tomlin is 50.Singer Barry Gibb is 43.   Thought for Today: ``The right of conquest has no foundationother than the right of the strongest.'' _ Jean Jacques Rousseau,French political philosopher (1712-1778).</TEXT><NOTE>End Advance for Use Friday, September 1</NOTE></DOC>